Task 1: Installing and Configuring Fail2Ban
Subtask 1.1: Install Fail2Ban
First, update your system and install Fail2Ban:

# Update package repositories
sudo apt update

# Install Fail2Ban
sudo apt install fail2ban -y

# Verify installation
fail2ban-client version
Subtask 1.2: Understanding Fail2Ban Structure
Explore the Fail2Ban directory structure:

# Navigate to Fail2Ban configuration directory
cd /etc/fail2ban

# List configuration files
ls -la

# View the main configuration file
sudo cat fail2ban.conf

# Check the jail configuration template
sudo cat jail.conf
Subtask 1.3: Create Local Configuration Files
Create local configuration files to avoid conflicts during updates:

# Create local jail configuration
sudo cp jail.conf jail.local

# Create local fail2ban configuration
sudo cp fail2ban.conf fail2ban.local

# Verify files were created
ls -la *.local
Subtask 1.4: Configure Basic Fail2Ban Settings
Edit the main Fail2Ban configuration:

# Edit fail2ban.local
sudo nano fail2ban.local
Add or modify these settings in the [Definition] section:

[Definition]
# Log level (CRITICAL, ERROR, WARNING, NOTICE, INFO, DEBUG)
loglevel = INFO

# Log target (/var/log/fail2ban.log, STDOUT, STDERR, SYSLOG)
logtarget = /var/log/fail2ban.log

# Socket file location
socket = /var/run/fail2ban/fail2ban.sock

# PID file location
pidfile = /var/run/fail2ban/fail2ban.pid

# Database file location
dbfile = /var/lib/fail2ban/fail2ban.sqlite3
Task 2: Configuring SSH Protection
Subtask 2.1: Enable SSH Jail
Edit the jail.local file to configure SSH protection:

# Edit jail configuration
sudo nano jail.local
Configure the [DEFAULT] section:

[DEFAULT]
# Ban time in seconds (10 minutes)
bantime = 600

# Find time window in seconds (10 minutes)
findtime = 600

# Maximum retry attempts
maxretry = 3

# Default backend for log monitoring
backend = auto

# Email settings (optional)
destemail = admin@yourdomain.com
sender = fail2ban@yourdomain.com

# Action to take when banning
action = %(action_)s
Enable and configure the SSH jail:

[sshd]
enabled = true
port = ssh
filter = sshd
logpath = /var/log/auth.log
maxretry = 3
bantime = 3600
findtime = 600
Subtask 2.2: Create Custom SSH Filter
Create a custom filter for enhanced SSH protection:

# Create custom SSH filter
sudo nano /etc/fail2ban/filter.d/sshd-custom.conf
Add the following content:

[Definition]
# Custom SSH filter with additional patterns
failregex = ^%(__prefix_line)s(?:error: PAM: )?[aA]uthentication (?:failure|error|failed) for .* from <HOST>( via \S+)?\s*$
            ^%(__prefix_line)s(?:error: )?Received disconnect from <HOST>: 3: .*: Auth fail$
            ^%(__prefix_line)sUser .+ from <HOST> not allowed because not listed in AllowUsers$
            ^%(__prefix_line)sUser .+ from <HOST> not allowed because listed in DenyUsers$
            ^%(__prefix_line)sUser .+ from <HOST> not allowed because not in any group$
            ^%(__prefix_line)srefused connect from \S+ \(<HOST>\)$
            ^%(__prefix_line)sReceived disconnect from <HOST>: 11: Bye Bye$
            ^%(__prefix_line)sConnection closed by <HOST>$

ignoreregex =

[Init]
# Define common prefix for log lines
__prefix_line = (?:(?:\S+ )?(?:kernel: )?(?:\[\s*\d+\.\d+\] )?(?:\S+\s+)?(?:\S+:\s+)?)?
